      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Certainly, textualism focuses on the plain meaning of the text at the time of enactment, which may seem more intellectually consistent for interpreting the Constitution in line with the founders' intentions. Conversely, the living Constitution approach argues for a more flexible interpretation that accounts for contemporary society. A textualist might claim this method honors the document's original context and authority, but a proponent of the living Constitution approach could argue that it reflects the evolving nature of American society and its values. Both philosophies have valid intellectual underpinnings, yet neither can claim absolute consistency in evaluating the founders' intentions or justice in contemporary application.",
